First, I would like to thank my PhD supervisors, Zsolt and Thomas, without whom this
project would never have started and could never have been conducted. This co-supervised
thesis would not have taught me so much without this "neuro/physics" duality. Thank you,
Thomas, for your guidance and for our numerous (and often lively!) discussions about the
future directions of fUSI and Iconeus. I know I can be stubborn when I'm passionate, and
I'm grateful for your support throughout this adventure. Thank you, Zsolt, for trusting
me so much during all these years and giving me the freedom to explore the directions I
thought were fruitful (while wisely hinting at those that would not work). Thank you
also for accepting yet another "engineer" student to work on fUSI alongside you in 2020,
when you were still hoping to recruit a "neuroscience" student! Although this PhD
officially started in December 2021, it truly began in your lab in January 2020. Thank
you both for your guidance---I can continue my academic adventure with confidence while
looking back on four amazing years of science.

I would also like to thank my jury for reviewing and discussing my work. Alessandro
Gozzi and David Maresca, thank you for carefully reviewing the manuscript and providing
precious comments. Pierre Pouget, Sara Stankowicz, Charlie Demené, and Luc Eglin, thank
you for being part of this jury and accepting to discuss my results on October 2nd. I
can't wait for this discussion and to receive feedback from such experts on my work. I
would also like to thank Nicolas Marie and Isabelle Rivals for being part of my thesis
advisory committee during these four years. Your remarks have helped shape the direction
of this work. Dear Isabelle, my love for statistics was born from your courses at ESPCI,
and I had the chance to receive your advice even before this PhD while working on
proteomics at the SMBP. I would surely not have pursued a career in this field if it
weren't for what you taught me. Your memory and influence live on in this work.

This PhD could not have been possible without the collaboration and funding from
Iconeus. I'd like to thank the whole team, and in particular Bruno Osmanski and Luc
Eglin, who supervised this PhD from the inside. You have offered me an amazing
environment to learn about the challenges and satisfactions of industrial R&D. You also
offered me the opportunity to see some of my PhD work become useful for practical
applications and offered to Iconeus clients, which brings even more meaning to this
work. Thank you for your supervision, your invaluable comments, and for our scientific
discussions, which always brought a new perspective to the usual academic mindset. At
Iconeus, I also want to thank Jeremy Ferrier for accepting to review my manuscript in
the final hours before submission and providing such detailed and helpful comments. As
Iconeus PhD students, we could always count on you, whether for scientific questions or
very practical administrative stuff. You're really the "fUSI genie" of the team, and my
time at Iconeus wouldn't have been the same without your help.

At the IPNP, I want to thank the Lenkei lab, both old and new members. In particular,
Diana Zala, Cyril Hanus, Renata Santos, Alexandre Varangot, and last but not least,
Louis Barthe. You were my anchor point to "true" neuroscience, and it's thanks to you
that I decided on pursuing a postdoc in this field. Louis, in particular, thank you for
our endless discussions about fUSI and for always being so motivated. I could always
count on you when I was split between the IPNP and Physmed.

At Physmed, I want to thank the whole team, from researchers to engineers and
administrative staff. It is truly a privilege to be surrounded by such a diverse group
with such beautiful projects. In particular, I want to thank my office-mates during
these four years: Mathis Vert, Adrien Bertolo, Felipe Cybis Pereira, Benjamin Guérif,
Henri Leroy, Jean-Baptiste Guillaumin, Thomas Bancel, Julie Uchitel, Auré Moisset, Oumou
Traore, Marie Duprat, Esteban Rivera. I'm convinved the legend will someday come
true---we'll get everyone in the office at the same time and somebody's PhD manuscript
chapter will write itself!

Among the wonderful groups I've had the chance to work with, some people deserve special
mention for their direct, or indirect, contributions to this work.

Henri Leroy, thank you for teaching me so much about acoustic physics and for our
endless discussions about SVD. Your expertise brought clarity to concepts I struggled
with, and our exchanges always pushed my understanding further.

Silvia Cazzanelli, thank you for your contagious smile and for inviting me to
participate in such great projects. Your positive energy always brightened the lab!

Nicolas Zucker, thank you for your motivation and your incredible drive for science.
This is the kind of drive that radiates onto others and pushes you to go even further.
Working alongside you has been truly inspiring.

Adrien Bertolo, thank you for teaching me so much about fUSI and for being so joyful and
supportive. Your enthusiasm has been contagious and made even the most challenging
moments lighter.

Andrea Kliewer, thank you for inviting us to work with you in Jena and making sure our
trip was so memorable. Your Opioids project was truly the most interesting one of my
PhD, and I'm grateful for the opportunity to be part of it.

Felipe Cybis Pereira, thank you for the friendship we forged around our scientific
discussions on fUSI, open science, and our work on PyfUS (and beyond!). We have
developed some amazing skills together, and I deeply hope that we will continue working
on the ideas we developed. My PhD would truly not have been the same without you.

Mathis Vert and Victor Blanvillain, my best men and closest friends. Although we have
collaborated little professionally, this work couldn't have been done without you. I
would have stopped my PhD long ago if it weren't for you both. Sharing the lab with you
was what kept me going, and I can't thank you enough for being there when it counted.

Jean-Charles Mariani, thank you for everything. None of this would have started if it
weren't for that serendipitous evening of November 24, 2019 at the Sputnik bar, where
you first explained your research and invited me to be your intern. You were (and still
are) my mentor in fUSI and neuroscience, instilled my love for research and my drive to
pursue academia. You were there when we went through political crises at the lab, and
you were there to remind me about my passion for research when it had left me. Thank you
for taking me under your wing and teaching me how to fly. I can't wait until we cross
paths again on the winding roads of research!

Beyond the lab, I want to thank my friends and family who supported me throughout this
journey. To my parents, thank you for your unconditional support and for always
believing in me. You pushed me to pursue my passions and ensured that I had the best
possible education. Your sacrifices have not gone unnoticed, and I am forever grateful.
You have given me the foundation and confidence to pursue my dreams.

To my family-in-law, thank you for welcoming me and for your encouragement throughout
these years. Your support has meant the world to me, and I am ever so proud to be a "Le
Meur-Diebolt"!

To my friends outside of science, thank you for reminding me that there is a world
beyond manuscripts and experiments, and for being there during the moments when I needed
to disconnect and recharge. Your presence has been essential in maintaining my balance
during these intense years.

Maude, none of this would have been possible without you, your unwavering support, your
companionship, your love. You saw me through four years of joy and tears, always being
there in the best and worst moments. You listened to my doubts, celebrated my small
victories, and reminded me why I started this journey when I lost sight of it. You
endured the late nights, the weekend, and the stress of deadlines with patience and
understanding. Along the way, we continued to grow together, we got married, and we
built a life that gave meaning to everything beyond these pages. I'm closing these 330
pages of my life loving you even more than when I began to write them, and I cannot wait
for all the chapters still to come. There are not enough words in this manuscript to
express how grateful I am for your affection and support.
_Tu es mon roc au jour de la détresse._ I dedicate this manuscript to you.
